post_text:
#204 Cross Country had a GREAT outing today! Soooo proud of our kids!

Kinlee Howell & Zach Teel each won their respective JV races. While Aubrey Keller (3rd), Brylee Russell (4th), Josie Bathon (5th), Allie Leonard (6th), Maddy Brand (8th), Victoria Barnes (9th) all were in the Top 10 in the Girls JV race. And, Jace Buza (2nd), Aiden Carter (3rd), Case Kellerman (4th), Jace Travelstead (6th), Carson Teel (7th), and Michael Sizemore (9th) all were in the Top 10 in the Boys JV race.

Girls Varsity had Vanessa Teel (4th), Jessie Baggett (5th), and Gia Pasquino (7th) all medal.

Boys Varsity saw great success with Thomas Fisher taking 1st. While Landen Carter (2nd), Landon Travelstead (3rd), Ayden Buza (5th), and Dylan Keller (9th) all medaling.

It was a great day with lots of PR's!

Dear Colleagues:

We are aware of a rumor circulating about the possibility of Governor Pritzker announcing at a press conference tomorrow a return to fully remote learning for the fall. We have confirmed with the Governor's Office that the rumor is false. At this time, there are no changes to the ISBE and IDPH joint transition guidance for fall.

Thank you for your ongoing partnership to serve our students safely.

Sincerely,

Dr. Carmen I. Ayala

post_text:
Can't begin to thank enough the volunteers who came out today to our 2nd Transition Team Meeting. We met for over 4 hours and discussed nearly every aspect of the school day as it pertains to re-opening for in person learning on August 17th.

It is a daunting task to say the least and I truly appreciate everyone's efforts.

We developed a survey that will help us tremendously to get a feel of how our parents feel towards several different topics concerning our transition to in person learning.

Parents please expect a call from your 2019-2020 teacher. They will be asking several questions that will help us in creating our plan. We have already did a lot of leg work in covering specifics. But we need your help to ensure this plan reflects our community.

Please feel free to be open and upfront with the survey. That is what we desire. There will for sure be changes logistically in the way we "do school".

Hope to see you all soon!

Mr. T.

post_text:
Just to keep everyone up to speed with accurate information I would like to mention the Executive Order signed by Governor Pritzker today.

This order does allow limited in-person Summer School activities to begin immediately. However, #204 does not currently have any Summer School activities going. Therefore, it does not apply to us.

This Executive Order has nothing to do with the upcoming 2020-2021 school year. It also has nothing to do with our athletics. I anticipate the IHSA's reccomendations for summer contact with students to soon be distributed, after being approved by the IDPH. The IHSA does not govern #204's athletics, however we would likely follow suit to what they are recommending, if we feel it is reasonable.

As for what to expect in the fall. All I can say is that this is definitely a step in the direction we, as a school district, feel is best for our kids. We are not there yet, but we are closer.

Mr. T

Never before has a group of #204 Tigers put in so much work, and had put themselves in a better position to win a Regional Title, and possibly grab a State Trophy for the first time ever in #204 History, than this group of girls.

We are so sorry, that due to circumstances out of their control, they will never get their opportunity. However, let's celebrate what this group has earned and accomplished either way. Way to go ladies!

#204 is very proud of you girls! We wish you great luck in your future.

Mr. T

Parents,

I want to keep you informed on how the Corona Virus effects us as a district. The teachers & I have a plan in the case we shut our doors for purposes related to this situation. At the moment the decision to shut down or not is being left to local control. However, that could change in a moments notice. As a district, we do not intend to close. However, if we do, we are prepared to do what we can to keep the education process moving forward as much as possible. No matter the decisions made, we hope to maintain your support throughout. Information will be shared as it is received.

Thanks to all the #204 Community and friends that helped sell 50/50 Tickets last night. Conditions were not the best, almost felt like we were in the movie Forrest Gump with all kinds of rain. However, I believe we made the most of it. It will be one of those experiences that we will definitely look back on and be able to remember. 5 or 10 years from now I'm sure the conditions will have gotten much worse through our story telling, lol. We have raised over $5000 over the past few years selling tickets. I'm very thankful for your commitment. And our little school is all the better because of it.

Mr. T

Back to back weeks and the Tigers are adding some more hardware to the trophy case!

Congratulations to the #204 Tiger Boys Cross Country Team for their 2nd Place finish at State!

Also, Congratulations to the 2019 Boys Individual State Champion Isaac Teel! Isaac came in at 9:54! That's approximately a pace of 5:18 per mile for nearly 2 miles.

Also medaling for the boys were Landen Carter (15th), Zach Teel (43rd), and Luke Drake (46th).

It's a great day to be a Tiger!

Pinckneyville Community Hospital
October 17, 2019 at 1:00 PM ·

!!Attention!!

Pinckneyville Community Hospital will be conducting an emergency preparedness drill on Friday, October 18. The drill will last from 8:00 a.m. until approximately 10:00 a.m.

The exercise will practice emergency response procedures to a simulated decontamination and hazmat situation at Pinckneyville Community Hospital and the Family Medical Center, and will involve the coordination of various community agencies and emergency response personnel.

The public should be advised that there will be an increase in personnel on site at Pinckneyville Community Hospital and the Family Medical Center during this time, but all business will continue to operate as normal.

Prior to the Softball team's State Championship game the #204 Tigers CC Team ran at Herrin. Here is Mr. Cupcake himself (a.k.a Zach Teel) doing his best impersonation of his big bro blowing away the competition in the 5th grade race. Zach is a great talent and the future is bright for the #204 CC Team.

The boys 5th grade team went 1st - Zach Teel (5th Grader), 3rd - Jace Buza (4th Grader), 6th - Aiden Carter (5th Grader), 7th - Case Kellerman (3rd Grader) and 16th - Jace Travelstead (3rd Grader). For a team total of 33. Awesome job boys!

The Tigers also medaled Gia Pasquino, Aubrey Keller, and Landen Carter. Several Tigers opted not to go to the meet due to the softball game.

post_text:
Our Girls will play in the semifinals of the state softball tourney Tuesday at 1 pm at Coulterville. We will be taking any 6th-8th grade student that would like to go. Due to the game not being over prior to 3 PM. Handwritten notes signed by parents are due tomorrow indicating the 6th-8th graders intentions for Tuesday (stay or go). Parents will have to pick up their students at #204 after returning after the game. The cost to attend will be covered.

All younger students signed out by parents, going to the game, will be an excused absence.

If the girls win Tuesday we will dismiss school Thursday at 2 pm. If they lose Tuesday we will do the exact same thing Thursday as we are doing tomorrow.

Cross Country will still have a meet on Thursday either way. The meet will be optional for the runners.

And don't forget Parent/Teacher Conferences are coming up soon as well.

Mr. T

Pinckneyville Community, this is an amazing girl that lives in our community. Give this real life interview a listen.

The #204 Cross Country Team is officially joining the 100 Mile Pledge. We will be logging all our runners miles for the month. We have 25 runners this year. Our challenge to you is you make a monetary donation for each runner that completes the 100 miles. Therefore if all 25 make it and you pledge $5 per runner that would come to a total of $125. If you pledge $1 per runner and all 25 make their goal that would be a $25 pledge.

If you would like to donate a flat amount or a per runner amount to the Cross Country Team's efforts please contact us anytime. Our goal for the month is $2040.

The #204 Cross Country Team is officially joining the 100 Mile Pledge. We will be logging all our runners miles for the month. We have 25 runners this year. Our challenge to you is you make a monetary donation for each runner that completes the 100 miles. Therefore if all 25 make it and you pledge $5 per runner that would come to a total of $125. If you pledge $1 per runner and all 25 make their goal that would be a $25 pledge.

If you would like to donate a flat amount or a per runner amount to the Cross Country Team's efforts please contact us anytime. Our goal for the month is $2040.

Kerry Marie Walker Drake is with Eric Drake.
September 1, 2019 at 6:50 PM ·

Here is a video of Nancy to
Kick off our month long pledge of walking 100 miles to raise awareness for childhood cancer!!

post_text: #204 is very proud to share that we now have a Special Olympics team at #204. Mr. T will be our Coach, and we hope to enlist some of our upper grade kids to help out as well. We will have some young people competing this school year and we couldn't be more excited. We are Region K and this Duck Derby fundraiser at the DQSF benefits our kiddos.

Rend Lake Project Office/ Visitor Center
August 21, 2019 at 4:33 PM ·

What do a Snake, Raccoon, Eurasian Eagle Owl, Harris Hawk, and a Fruit Bat all have in common?

They will all be at the Rend Lake Visitor Center this Saturday for the Animal Senses program with Bob Tarter. This is one of the highlight programs for the Environmental Science Series each year. You will be able to get an upclose view of these anilmals as you learn about their key senses and how they use them to thrive.

We will have programs at 11:00 AM and 2:00 PM. Please come early, as the seating is limited to 90 seats per program and you will want a good seat for this one.
